	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9666765786216><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=9666765786216>Getting the mob to stay with the pet</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=9666765786216#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Aug 19th 5:16 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.33]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Very often, one of the main requirements of a mage is to get the mob to stay on your pet while you are blasting it.<br><br>As you all know, this can be rather troublesome. Very often, after one or two blasts, the mob starts hitting you. Which can often result in you running around until it hits your pet.<br><br>Here are my humble observations :-<br><br>Generally, mobs will not switch to you when you initially blast them. Or in other words, blast number one does not pull it off the pet but blast number two will.<br><br>However, once your pet is down to about 50% hit points, then all your blasting will not pull it off the pet.<br><br>So the main tactic is to blast it once, let the pet fight for a while. Wait till the pet is at 50% HP. Then start hosing the mob down.<br><br>You might want to put a few pet healing spells between your blasts. Just to keep your pet alive.<br><br><br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
