	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96662250310838><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=96662250310838>My pet methods</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=96662250310838#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=606><span id=Sage>Yegolev</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>192 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 2:15 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.40]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There are obviously many philosophies on which pet to use, and everyone seems to be saying something different!&nbsp;&nbsp;Why is that?  There are just far too many factors to boil down pet selection to just saying one or the other is better.  This is a short list of reasons I choose a particular pet, sorted by pet type.<br><br>Earth: Definitely one of the favorites, especially with the powerleveler crowd.  This is because the earth pet's high HP allows it to stand against yellows and reds longer.  Given the level difference when fighting yellows and reds, even your air pet will be taking hits much as you do when meleeing higher level creatures.  This is a situation where using a damage shield is very important, since your DD has a higher chance of being resisted by your yellow/red target.<br><br>Water: Another one of the favorites, it replaces the earth pet's root with a damage spell.  The real utility of the water pet lies in its immunity to poison, and the water pet should be used in any encounter with mobs that cast poison.  Less HP and no root means you'll need to be on your toes a bit more and flee early, but with proper judgement you have a very useful tool for killing snakes and spiders.  As usual, damage shields are a good thing to use.<br><br>Fire: Sometimes you just can't get someplace with yellow/red mobs and are forced to hunt evens and blues with the common folk.  This is the place I prefer to use the fire pet.  In the situation where your pet is within one level of the mob, the extra damage of a fire pet outweighs the extra absorption an earth pet has because it allows me to drop the mobs more quickly and get on with my hunting.  An even mob will give less XP per kill so I make up for that lack by killing in volume, and the fire pet helps me do that.<br><br>Air: My success with air has rested solely on its ability to turn invisible, however in a group situation the stun effect can be a real tank-pleaser.  Stunning the mob(s) will only decrease your tank's downtime (even if YOU are the tank) by reducing the damage output of the mob.  Another crowd-pleasing effect is that in weirdly-pathed zones where your pet goes nuts (Crushbone, for example) the invisibility factor allows a more relaxed atmosphere during downtime... unless of course you're in an area where the mobs can see invis.<br><br>I suppose to sum up, I use fire and earth depending on my prey's level.  Against poison I use water, and I hardly ever use air.  Your mileage may vary.<br>&nbsp;<br>www.yegolev.com<br>Ibaler the Valewalker<br>Gaheris</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
