	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96704719725252><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=96704719725252>RE: My pet methods</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=96704719725252#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Aug 23rd 12:13 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I agree with you about the use of fire pets to kill a lot of blue cons. However that only works at low and middle levels. Once you get to higher levels blues will be all that you will be able to kill(well whites too). I totally disagree with you about your statement on air pets. You oviosly aren't a higher level magician becuase you talk about kill yellows and reds. At higher levels you WILL NOT be able to kill a red or yellow. At your best you will be able to take whites. Although I agree that at lower levels the air pet is not as usefull as the other pets. However once you get to higher levels and pets can duel-wield, their true power comes out. <br><br>Here is what I posted earlier on another spot in this forum. Rate me good =;-) .<br><br>FIRE PET: Someone said that fire pets are the best soloing pets levels 16-24. He said you can sic your fire pet on the enemy and just stand back and heal. Well guess what, you DO NOT want to do that. Why not? Becuase then your pet will take half the exp. from the kill. If you are using a pet and it outdamages you, you only get half the exp. for the kill. If you outdamage your pet you get the full exp. for the kill. Fire pets are good for fast kills or to clear out a whole bunch of green cons. Example: my guild decides to raid Splitpaw to get some of the items dropped by the higher level gnolls. We were all levels 40+. All those tesch mass gnolls conned green, so killing them we get us No exp., yet they would assist the higher levels gnolls. I bring a fire pet out and he smashes them up very quickly. I really never use a fire pet except for that. <br><br>EARTH PET: Good pet for soloing IN CERTAIN SITUATIONS. Its not always the best choice. It has massive hp, casts root, and will make full-use of your damage shields(becuase of low agility). The problem with it? It has very low AC, so it will be taking a lot of damage per hit from the things you are fighting. IT IS NOT the pet you want for taking a quick spawning thing. It has tons of hp, but after the battle and its down to about 30% hp, it definately won't be ready for the next spawn thats up in 5 minutes. You would have to spend your mana on healing it, but then thats a waste becuase then you won't have enough mana when the spawn comes up. Also DO NOT use this pet when you are grouping and there is someone in the group with snare. The root the pet casts will remove the snare and start trains. Also DO NOT use this pet when soloing things that run away WHEN OUTDOORS. If you are soloing something that runs away when it gets down to 10% health, the earth pet will root it and it will keep fighting, and your pet will keep taking more damage or possibly die. Now if you are soloing things that run away at high-speed, thats a different story. Overall, this is an excellent pet for soloing at the low levels or when the root effect is needed. <br><br>AIR PET: This is my favorite pet. They have insane amounts of agility, dexterity, and AC, plus attack faster than all the other pets AND do a stun spell. It is VERY good for when you are fighting casting mobs and IMO the best pet for grouping. They are also the best pets for kiting. Send this pet in on your enemy and then blast them until they come after you. Then just start to run away. The pet will stun the enemy while you are running, which is a HUGE taunt. Then you just stop running, blast again, run more until pet stuns, blast more, etc. until the thing is dead. You can kite well without SOW and j-boots becuase of a pathing bug. Want to know it? While running hit the numberlock button. This will make you run continusly. Then after hitting the number lock button, hold the Crtl key and one of the left or right running buttons. The effect: you will strafe WHILE running making it so most mobs won't be able to catch up with you and giving you the speed of j-boots without having them. Pretty cool huh. Also, becuase of its massive dexterity it will become a complete destoryer when you give it a couple gnoll-hide lariats or rune swords. With its haste bonus and massive-procing it will actually do MORE damage than a fire pet when grouping(since the fire pet usually won't be getting hit, and therefore wasting its damage shield, which is the main reason it does so much damage). Overall: I love this pet. It isn't as effective until the mid levels(about 20), so at lower levels you will want to use another pet. However, once you get to higher levels and it gets a haste bonus and starts stunning more, you will love it. <br><br>WATER PET: This is the completley balanced pet. It has the 2nd best hp, agility, and AC of all the pets. Also it regens it HP faster than the other pets and is completely IMMUNE to poison. I use this pet when camping a really quick spawn, fighting things that have a NASTY poison attack, or when in a pure caster group where the pets will be tanking, and they need to regen their hp quickly. If you are a poor magician at the lower levels you can just buy only this pet and still do alright. However, once you get to higher levels you WILL need to start getting other pets(and even at lower levels other pets are better in certain situations). <br><br>Zuranthium/Corpusnuntia/Sunsong/Naltec/Divineshadow<br><br>Player of many characters on the Namless.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
