	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96655038211335><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=96655038211335>Xalick - Bertoxx</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=96655038211335#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 17th 6:13 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.18]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ahh...Magicians...the masters of summoning. Most important thing to remember is ALWAYS have a pet up before you engage in combat. As far as i'm concerned a magician IS his or her pet (moreso at higher lvls then lower) and if you lose your pet in combat you are pretty well done with as you have no way to crowd control. No root, stuns, fear, nada.<br><br>If you are soloing the most effective pet is definately Earth as he can withstand much more damage than any of the other pets and has the ability to root. Start by buffing your pet with Burnout and a Damage Shield - pull the mob with Malise/Malisement/Malosi - send your pet in for combat - give your pet a bit of time to create an aggro and root the mob then blast to your hearts content. The mob will want to start pounding on you from chain blasting but because he is being rooted by your pet he is unable to get to you. Malise helps a great deal in having your pet successfully root the mob as is lowers Magic Resist (along with poison, fire, and cold).<br><br>Group strategy, however, is much different. Your main goal is to maximize damage while allowing the tank(s) to keep the mob aggro'd on them. You can do this by waiting a while before you start to blast....this will give the tank the time s/he needs to taunt the mob well enough so that it will stay on him. Once you have given the tank some time to taunt you may start blasting. However one important thing to remember is to space your blasts apart for the same reason you gave the tank time in the beginning of battle, to keep the mob on him. Pet selection for groups is also different as the majority of group you will have someone who can Snare or Darkness the mobs. You therefore do not want an earth pet as his root will break the snare or darkness which is better than root. When a mob is snared or darknessed they will stop all movement and melee combat when they get low enough health, however if they are rooted they stop all movement but continue to melee no matter how low they are on health. Your best pet therefore is probably your Fire Pet as he has a self damage shield and delivers a decent DD spell to help down the mobs faster.<br><br>For those that may be wondering, the reason it is so important to keep the mob on the tank is because he will have much higher Armor Class and Hit Points than you. Because he has high AC he will get hit much less often and when he does get hit it will be for less damage which saves the healers (the backbone of a group) mana. Also, because you have much fewer HP's your health bar will drop alot faster than the tanks which creates alot of stress for the healer as he will end up having to chain heal. Chain healing is a VERY bad thing as it creates a very large aggro on the healer. The mobs can potentially swarm the healer making it nearly impossible for him to cast, therefore resulting in no more heals...<br><br>Theres my two copper....enjoy<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
